{"title_page": "Albacora-Leste oil field", "text_new": "{{Infobox oilfield\n| name        = Albacora-Leste Oil Field\n| country     = [[Brazil]]\n| region      = [[Campos Basin]]\n| location    = \n| block       = \n| offonshore  = offshore\n| coordinates = \n| operator    = [[Petrobras]]\n| operators   = \n| partners    = \n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| discovery   = 1986\n| start_development = \n| start_production = 1987\n| peak_year   =\n| abandonment =\n| oil_production_bbl/d = 180000\n| oil_production_tpy =\n| production_year_oil = \n| production_gas_mmcuft/d =\n| production_gas_mmscm/d =\n| production_gas_bcm/y =\n| production_year_gas =\n| est_oil_bbl = 534\n| est_oil_t   = 72\n| est_gas_bft = 183\n| est_gas_bcm = 5.2\n| formations  =\n}}\n\nThe '''Albacora-Leste Oil Field''' is an [[oil field]] located in [[Campos Basin]]. It was discovered in 1986 and developed by [[Petrobras]].  The oil field is operated by [[Petrobras]], that owns 90% of the field, while [[Repsol]] owns the remaining 10%.<ref name='presal'>{{Cite web |url=http://fatosedados.blogspetrobras.com.br/2010/06/23/descoberta-de-indicios-de-petroleo-no-pre-sal-em-albacora-leste |title=Descoberta de ind\u00edcios de petr\u00f3leo no pr\u00e9-sal em Albacora Leste |author=Petrobras |date=2010 |accessdate=January 28, 2014 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121231125937/http://fatosedados.blogspetrobras.com.br/2010/06/23/descoberta-de-indicios-de-petroleo-no-pre-sal-em-albacora-leste |archive-date=2012-12-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The total [[proven reserves]] of the Albacora-Leste oil field are around 534 million barrels (72\u00d710<sup>6</sup>tonnes), and production is centered on {{convert|180000|oilbbl/d|m3/d}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lngplants.com/Brazil.html|title=Repsol YPF 3rd  Largest Oil Producer in Brazil 2006|year=2006|publisher=lngplants.com|accessdate=2013-06-09}}</ref>\n\n==Geology==\nThe Albacora field consists of a several producing horizons of [[Albian]] to [[Miocene]] [[sandstone]] [[turbidites]], with an area of 235&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=Candido>Candido, A., and Cora, C.A.G., 1992, The Marlim and Albacora Giant Fields, Campos Basin, Offshore Brazil, AAPG Memoir 54, Halbouty, M.T., editor, Tulsa: American Association of Petroleum Geologists, {{ISBN|0891813330}}</ref>{{rp|124}}  [[Reflection seismology]] in 1972 disclosed a [[fault (geology)|faulted]] [[anticline]] and seismic amplitude [[bright spot]], which was drilled by wildcat 1-RJS-297 in 1984 and discovered oil.<ref name=Candido/>{{rp|126}}  The [[stratigraphy]] of the Campos Basin starts with the [[Lower Cretaceous]] Lago Feia [[Formation (stratigraphy)|Formation]] a [[source rock]], followed by the [[Albian]] Macae Formation  consisting of shallow water carbonates overlain by late Albian [[shale]]s, [[marl]]s, [[calcilutite]]s, and [[turbidite]] [[sandstone]]s.<ref name=Candido/>{{rp|128}}  From this formation through most of the [[Cenozoic]], the Campos Formation was deposited, consisting of deep water turbiditic sandstones and shales, the main producers in the Albacora and [[Marlim]] fields.<ref name=Candido/>{{rp|129}}  Finally, the basin was filled by the Ubatuba Formation, consisting of slope and shelf deposits.<ref name=Candido/>{{rp|129}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Brazil|Energy}}\n{{coord missing|Brazil}}\n\n[[Category:Oil fields of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Campos Basin]]\n[[Category:Petrobras]]\n[[Category:Petrobras Operated Oil and Gas Fields]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox oilfield\n| name        = Albacora-Leste Oil Field\n| country     = [[Brazil]]\n| region      = [[Campos Basin]]\n| location    = \n| block       = \n| offonshore  = offshore\n| coordinates = \n| operator    = [[Petrobras]]\n| operators   = \n| partners    = \n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| discovery   = 1986\n| start_development = \n| start_production = 1987\n| peak_year   =\n| abandonment =\n| oil_production_bbl/d = 180000\n| oil_production_tpy =\n| production_year_oil = \n| production_gas_mmcuft/d =\n| production_gas_mmscm/d =\n| production_gas_bcm/y =\n| production_year_gas =\n| est_oil_bbl = 534\n| est_oil_t   = 72\n| est_gas_bft = 183\n| est_gas_bcm = 5.2\n| formations  =\n}}\n\nThe '''Albacora-Leste Oil Field''' is an [[oil field]] located in [[Campos Basin]]. It was discovered in 1986 and developed by [[Petrobras]].  The oil field is operated by [[Petrobras]], that owns 90% of the field, while [[Repsol]] owns the remaining 10%.<ref name='presal'>{{Cite web |url=http://fatosedados.blogspetrobras.com.br/2010/06/23/descoberta-de-indicios-de-petroleo-no-pre-sal-em-albacora-leste |title=Descoberta de ind\u00edcios de petr\u00f3leo no pr\u00e9-sal em Albacora Leste |author=Petrobras |date=2010 |accessdate=January 28, 2014 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121231125937/http://fatosedados.blogspetrobras.com.br/2010/06/23/descoberta-de-indicios-de-petroleo-no-pre-sal-em-albacora-leste |archive-date=2012-12-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The total [[proven reserves]] of the Albacora-Leste oil field are around 534 million barrels (72\u00d710<sup>6</sup>tonnes), and production is centered on {{convert|180000|oilbbl/d|m3/d}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lngplants.com/Brazil.html|title=Repsol YPF 3rd  Largest Oil Producer in Brazil 2006|year=2006|publisher=lngplants.com|accessdate=2013-06-09}}</ref>\n\n==Geology==\nThe Albacora field consists of a several producing horizons of [[Albian]] to [[Miocene]] [[sandstone]] [[turbidites]], with an area of 235&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=Candido>Candido, A., and Cora, C.A.G., 1992, The Marlim and Albacora Giant Fields, Campos Basin, Offshore Brazil, AAPG Memoir 54, Halbouty, M.T., editor, Tulsa: American Association of Petroleum Geologists, {{ISBN|0891813330}}</ref>{{rp|124}}  [[Reflection seismology]] in 1972 disclosed a [[fault (geology)|faulted]] [[anticline]] and seismic amplitude [[bright spot]], which was drilled by wildcat 1-RJS-297 in 1984 and discovered oil.<ref name=Candido/>{{rp|126}}  The [[stratigraphy]] of the Campos Basin starts with the [[Lower Cretaceous]] Lago Feia [[Formation (stratigraphy)|Formation]] a [[source rock]], followed by the [[Albian]] Macae Formation  consisting of shallow water carbonates overlain by late Albian [[shale]]s, [[marl]]s, [[calcilutite]]s, and [[turbidite]] [[sandstone]]s.<ref name=Candido/>{{rp|128}}  From this formation through most of the [[Cenozoic]], the Campos Formation was deposited, consisting of deep water turbiditic sandstones and shales, the main producers in the Albacora and [[Marlim]] fields.<ref name=Candido/>{{rp|129}}  Finally, the basin was filled by the Ubatuba Formation, consisting of slope and shelf deposits.<ref name=Candido/>{{rp|129}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Brazil|Energy}}\n{{coord missing|Brazil}}\n\n[[Category:Oil fields of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Campos Basin]]\n", "name_user": "QuinhodaBella", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added Petrobras and Petrobras Operated Oil and Gas Fields categories", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albacora-Leste_oil_field"}
{"title_page": "TV Junkie", "text_new": "{{short description|2006 film by Michael Cain, Matt Radecki}}\n'''''TV Junkie''''' is a documentary that chronicles Rick Kirkham's drug addiction.<ref>[http://www.hbo.com/addiction/thefilm/related/671_tvjunkie.html HBO website, TV Junkie page]</ref>  Its filmmakers, Michael Cain and Matt Radecki, sifted through the video-diary footage to piece together the story of Kirkham's life, focusing on the seven years in which he and his family struggled with his addiction to crack cocaine. It was shown at [[Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]] in 2006.<ref name=variety/> The film was the subject of a lawsuit by his ex-wife Tammie.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilonsky|first=Robert|title=TV Junkie Premieres on HBO Tonight -- And, Now, With a Lawsuit!|url=http://blogs.dallasobserver.com/unfairpark/2007/03/tv_junkie_premieres_on_hbo_ton.php|newspaper=Dallas Observer|date=Mar 16, 2007}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' gave the film a middling review, finding the central figure unpleasant and unsympathetic and the production values inevitably low.<ref name=variety>{{cite web|last=Foundas|first=Scott|title=TV Junkie|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117929801/?categoryid=31&cs=1|work=Variety|date=Feb 28, 2006}}</ref> Film Threat found it \"an unbelievably candid glimpse into the contradictions of cocaine addiction\", and praised Kirkham's articulate and authentic self-portrait.<ref>{{cite web|last=Foster|first=Sally|title=TV JUNKIE|url=http://www.filmthreat.com/reviews/8340/|work=Film Threat|date=November 2, 2006}}</ref> OutNow.CH found it had a certain fascination beyond what would be expected.<ref>{{cite web|title=TV Junkie (2006)|url=http://outnow.ch/Movies/2006/TVJunkie/Reviews/kino/|work=OutNow.CH|accessdate=30 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Rick Kirkham==\nRick Kirkham was a reporter for ''[[Inside Edition]]'' who appeared on a segment called \"Inside Adventure\". From the age of 14, he filmed more than 3,000 hours of a video diary; this included footage during his tenure on ''Inside Edition'' during which he was addicted to [[crack cocaine]].<ref>{{cite news|last=DONALDSON JAMES|first=SUSAN|title='TV Junkie' Used as Classroom Anti-Drug Tool|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/WaterCooler/story?id=4316482&page=1|newspaper=ABC|date=Feb 22, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' in 2007 to talk about his addiction, and clips of his video diary were shown.<ref>[http://www2.oprah.com/tows/pastshows/200704/tows_past_20070409.jhtmlOprah.com Oprah episode, \"Addiction: Why Can't They Stop?\"]</ref>  On ''Oprah'', Kirkham said he was a functional addict, and that he would smoke crack at night instead of sleeping, remaining high for about six hours, and report for work at ''Inside Edition'' two hours later.  Kirkham went days without sleep during this time.  He said he once interviewed President [[George H. W. Bush]] while high on crack; the subject was drug abuse. This is where his fate was decided.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0492494|TV Junkie}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''TV Junkie''}}\n\n{{Tiger King}}\n\n[[Category:2006 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about drug addiction]]\n[[Category:2000s documentary films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about journalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2006 film by Michael Cain, Matt Radecki}}\n'''''TV Junkie''''' is a documentary that chronicles Rick Kirkham's drug addiction.<ref>[http://www.hbo.com/addiction/thefilm/related/671_tvjunkie.html HBO website, TV Junkie page]</ref>  Its filmmakers, Michael Cain and Matt Radecki, sifted through the video-diary footage to piece together the story of Kirkham's life, focusing on the seven years in which he and his family struggled with his addiction to crack cocaine. It was shown at [[Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]] in 2006.<ref name=variety/> The film was the subject of a lawsuit by his ex-wife Tammie.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilonsky|first=Robert|title=TV Junkie Premieres on HBO Tonight -- And, Now, With a Lawsuit!|url=http://blogs.dallasobserver.com/unfairpark/2007/03/tv_junkie_premieres_on_hbo_ton.php|newspaper=Dallas Observer|date=Mar 16, 2007}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' gave the film a middling review, finding the central figure unpleasant and unsympathetic and the production values inevitably low.<ref name=variety>{{cite web|last=Foundas|first=Scott|title=TV Junkie|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117929801/?categoryid=31&cs=1|work=Variety|date=Feb 28, 2006}}</ref> Film Threat found it \"an unbelievably candid glimpse into the contradictions of cocaine addiction\", and praised Kirkham's articulate and authentic self-portrait.<ref>{{cite web|last=Foster|first=Sally|title=TV JUNKIE|url=http://www.filmthreat.com/reviews/8340/|work=Film Threat|date=November 2, 2006}}</ref> OutNow.CH found it had a certain fascination beyond what would be expected.<ref>{{cite web|title=TV Junkie (2006)|url=http://outnow.ch/Movies/2006/TVJunkie/Reviews/kino/|work=OutNow.CH|accessdate=30 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Rick Kirkham==\nRick Kirkham was a reporter for ''[[Inside Edition]]'' who appeared on a segment called \"Inside Adventure\". From the age of 14, he filmed more than 3,000 hours of a video diary; this included footage during his tenure on ''Inside Edition'' during which he was addicted to [[crack cocaine]].<ref>[http://www.bobrivers.com/ontheshow/brsnews.asp?artid=6961&cat=10&dismode=article BobRivers.com]</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=DONALDSON JAMES|first=SUSAN|title='TV Junkie' Used as Classroom Anti-Drug Tool|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/WaterCooler/story?id=4316482&page=1|newspaper=ABC|date=Feb 22, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' in 2007 to talk about his addiction, and clips of his video diary were shown.<ref>[http://www2.oprah.com/tows/pastshows/200704/tows_past_20070409.jhtmlOprah.com Oprah episode, \"Addiction: Why Can't They Stop?\"]</ref>  On ''Oprah'', Kirkham said he was a functional addict, and that he would smoke crack at night instead of sleeping, remaining high for about six hours, and report for work at ''Inside Edition'' two hours later.  Kirkham went days without sleep during this time.  He said he once interviewed President [[George H. W. Bush]] while high on crack; the subject was drug abuse. This is where his fate was decided.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0492494|TV Junkie}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''TV Junkie''}}\n\n{{Tiger King}}\n\n[[Category:2006 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about drug addiction]]\n[[Category:2000s documentary films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about journalists]]\n", "name_user": "Newyork12", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRick Kirkham:BobRivers.com dead link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TV_Junkie"}
{"title_page": "Jenni Russell", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Jenni Russell\n| image       =  Jenni Russell.png\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     =  \n| birthname   = Jenni Cecily Russell\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1960|07|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Johannesburg]], [[Transvaal (province)|Transvaal]], South Africa\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater  = [[St Catharine's College, Cambridge]]\n| occupation  = [[Writing|Columnist]] \n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Stephen Lambert (media executive)|Stephen Lambert]]|1988}}\n| children    = 2\n| known_for   = {{ubl|Columnist at ''[[The Times]]''|Columnist at ''[[The New York Times]]''|Former editor of ''[[The World Tonight]]''}}\n}}\n\n'''Jenni Cecily Russell''' (born 16 July 1960)<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U254175|title=Who's Who|year=2011}}</ref> is a British [[journalist]] and broadcaster. She is a columnist for ''[[The Times]]'', a contributing writer for ''[[The New York Times]]'', and a book reviewer for ''[[The Sunday Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/profile/jenni-russell?page=1 |title=Jenni Russell - The Times |newspaper=[[The Times]] |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/column/jenni-russell |title=Jenni Russell - The New York Times |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> She has been a columnist for ''[[The Guardian]]'' and written the political column for ''[[London Evening Standard]]''. \n\nShe worked for many years at the BBC and ITN, latterly as editor of ''[[The World Tonight]]'' on [[BBC Radio 4]]. She is married to [[Stephen Lambert (media executive)|Stephen Lambert]], a media executive, and lives in London.\n\n==Career==\nRussell studied history at [[St Catharine's College, Cambridge]], and went on to become a BBC News trainee. She worked for the BBC, as well as [[ITN]] and [[Channel 4 News]]. In 1998 she became joint editor of [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[The World Tonight]]'', becoming one of the first people to pioneer job-sharing within the BBC.\n\nOn leaving the BBC, Russell began writing comment pieces for ''[[The Guardian]]'' and the ''[[New Statesman]]'', before beginning to write regularly for ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', for whom she also reviews books. She has been a vocal critic of the failings of the education system and criticised the increasing abuse of civil liberties under the last Labour government.\n\nAccording to [[Peter Hoskin]] writing in ''[[The Spectator]]'' she is a key figure in the New Establishment, due to her friendship with both [[Steve Hilton]], [[David Cameron]]'s director of strategy, and [[Ed Miliband]], the former Labour leader.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hoskin |first=Peter |author-link=Peter Hoskin |date=10 October 2010 |title=Cameron's tangled web |url=https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2010/10/camerons-tangled-web/ |newspaper=[[The Spectator]] |access-date=14 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe was tipped as one of the candidates to be the next controller of [[BBC Radio 4]] in 2010, following the resignation of [[Mark Damazer]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/14/mark-damazer-radio-4|title=BBC seeks new Radio 4 controller after Mark Damazer steps down|first1=Jemima|last1=Kiss|first2=Maggie|last2=Brown|first3=Mark|last3=Sweney|date=14 April 2010|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011 she won the [[Orwell Prize]] for Political Journalism,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theorwellprize.co.uk/news/orwell-prize-2011-winners-announced/ |title=Orwell Prize 2011 winners announced \u2013 The Orwell Prize |publisher=Theorwellprize.co.uk |date=17 May 2011 |accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> having been shortlisted for the Commentariat of the Year at the 2010 Comment Awards.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20111005203737/http://www.editorialintelligence.com/special-events_17_1461087199.pdf</ref>\n\nShe was described as \"the stand-out journalist in an outstanding field\". The judges commented:\n\n\"Her empathy for the world beyond Westminster gives her writing an extra dimension often lacking in political insiders. There is an overriding humanity to her work, whether she is covering the death-throes of the last Labour government or the birth-pangs of the Coalition.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/may/18/jenni-russell-orwell-prize-political-journalism|title=Jenni Russell wins Orwell prize for political journalism|first=Jason|last=Deans|date=18 May 2011|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nShe wrote the Monday political column for the ''[[London Evening Standard]]'' for two years, from 2011 to 2013, and was shortlisted for the inaugural [[Hatchet Job of the Year]] Award in 2012 for her work on as a book reviewer in ''[[The Sunday Times]]''.\n\nIn 2013, she became a member of the independent expert panel advising the Government on the initiation and publication of Serious Case Reviews, and in August that year began writing a column on Thursdays for ''[[The Times]]''. At the 2015 Comment Awards she was named Society & Diversity Commentator of the Year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.commentawards.com/winners.php |title=The Comment Awards 2016 |publisher=Commentawards.com |accessdate=14 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129014215/http://www.commentawards.com/winners.php |archive-date=29 January 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, she profiled the Prime Minister, [[David Cameron]], for ''[[The Times]]'' on the eve of the UK general election,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/magazine/article4391549.ece|title=24 hours with David Cameron  |newspaper=[[The Times]]|access-date=21 March 2016}}</ref> and in April 2016 she profiled the US Ambassador to the UK, [[Matthew Barzun]], also for ''[[The Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/past-six-days/2016-04-16/the-times-magazine/yes-we-can-mr-president-5gjmx7mtp|title=Yes, we can, Mr President |newspaper=[[The Times]]|access-date=19 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, she once again interviewed Prime Minister Cameron for ''The Times Magazine'', this time ahead of the European Referendum.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/five-days-to-go-whats-he-really-thinking-xsgxkznzb|title=On the campaign trail with David Cameron  |newspaper=[[The Times]]|access-date=22 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nRussell regularly appears on television and radio, on programmes such as the [[BBC]]'s ''[[Newsnight]]'' and [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s ''[[The Agenda with Tom Bradby]]'', as well as [[Sky News]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|40em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/public/profile/Jenni-Russell ''The Times'' \u2013 Jenni Russell] profile page\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/profile/jennirussell ''The Guardian'' \u2013 Jenni Russell] profile page\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Russell, Jenni}}\n[[Category:Alumni of St Catharine's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:BBC newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:British journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The Times journalists]]\n[[Category:The Sunday Times people]]\n[[Category:London Evening Standard people]]\n[[Category:The Guardian journalists]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Jenni Russell\n| image       =  Jenni Russell.png\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     =  \n| birthname   = Jenni Cecily Russell\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1960|07|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Johannesburg]], [[Transvaal (province)|Transvaal]], South Africa\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater  = [[St Catharine's College, Cambridge]]\n| occupation  = [[Writing|Columnist]] \n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Stephen Lambert (media executive)|Stephen Lambert]]|1988}}\n| children    = 2\n| known_for   = {{ubl|Columnist at ''[[The Times]]''|Columnist at ''[[The New York Times]]''|Former editor of ''[[The World Tonight]]''}}\n}}\n\n'''Jenni Cecily Russell''' (born 16 July 1960)<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U254175|chapter=Russell, Jenni Cecily, (born 16 July 1960), newspaper columnist, since 2002|title=Who's Who|year=2011}}</ref> is a British [[journalist]] and broadcaster. She is a columnist for ''[[The Times]]'', a contributing writer for ''[[The New York Times]]'', and a book reviewer for ''[[The Sunday Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/profile/jenni-russell?page=1 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/column/jenni-russell |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> She has been a columnist for ''[[The Guardian]]'' and written the political column for ''[[London Evening Standard]]''. \n\nShe worked for many years at the BBC and ITN, latterly as editor of ''[[The World Tonight]]'' on [[BBC Radio 4]]. She is married to [[Stephen Lambert (media executive)|Stephen Lambert]], a media executive, and lives in London.\n\n==Career==\nRussell studied history at [[St Catharine's College, Cambridge]], and went on to become a BBC News trainee. She worked for the BBC, as well as [[ITN]] and [[Channel 4 News]]. In 1998 she became joint editor of [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[The World Tonight]]'', becoming one of the first people to pioneer job-sharing within the BBC.\n\nOn leaving the BBC, Russell began writing comment pieces for ''[[The Guardian]]'' and the ''[[New Statesman]]'', before beginning to write regularly for ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', for whom she also reviews books. She has been a vocal critic of the failings of the education system and criticised the increasing abuse of civil liberties under the last Labour government.\n\nAccording to [[Peter Hoskin]] writing in ''[[The Spectator]]'' she is a key figure in the New Establishment, due to her friendship with both [[Steve Hilton]], [[David Cameron]]'s director of strategy, and [[Ed Miliband]], the former Labour leader.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hoskin |first=Peter |author-link=Peter Hoskin |date=10 October 2010 |title=Cameron's tangled web |url=https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2010/10/camerons-tangled-web/ |newspaper=[[The Spectator]] |access-date=14 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe was tipped as one of the candidates to be the next controller of [[BBC Radio 4]] in 2010, following the resignation of [[Mark Damazer]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/14/mark-damazer-radio-4|title=BBC seeks new Radio 4 controller after Mark Damazer steps down|first1=Jemima|last1=Kiss|first2=Maggie|last2=Brown|first3=Mark|last3=Sweney|date=14 April 2010|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011 she won the [[Orwell Prize]] for Political Journalism,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theorwellprize.co.uk/news/orwell-prize-2011-winners-announced/ |title=Orwell Prize 2011 winners announced \u2013 The Orwell Prize |publisher=Theorwellprize.co.uk |date=17 May 2011 |accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> having been shortlisted for the Commentariat of the Year at the 2010 Comment Awards.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20111005203737/http://www.editorialintelligence.com/special-events_17_1461087199.pdf</ref>\n\nShe was described as \"the stand-out journalist in an outstanding field\". The judges commented:\n\n\"Her empathy for the world beyond Westminster gives her writing an extra dimension often lacking in political insiders. There is an overriding humanity to her work, whether she is covering the death-throes of the last Labour government or the birth-pangs of the Coalition.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/may/18/jenni-russell-orwell-prize-political-journalism|title=Jenni Russell wins Orwell prize for political journalism|first=Jason|last=Deans|date=18 May 2011|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nShe wrote the Monday political column for the ''[[London Evening Standard]]'' for two years, from 2011 to 2013, and was shortlisted for the inaugural [[Hatchet Job of the Year]] Award in 2012 for her work on as a book reviewer in ''[[The Sunday Times]]''.\n\nIn 2013, she became a member of the independent expert panel advising the Government on the initiation and publication of Serious Case Reviews, and in August that year began writing a column on Thursdays for ''[[The Times]]''. At the 2015 Comment Awards she was named Society & Diversity Commentator of the Year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.commentawards.com/winners.php |title=The Comment Awards 2016 |publisher=Commentawards.com |accessdate=14 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129014215/http://www.commentawards.com/winners.php |archive-date=29 January 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, she profiled the Prime Minister, [[David Cameron]], for ''[[The Times]]'' on the eve of the UK general election,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/magazine/article4391549.ece|title=24 hours with David Cameron  |newspaper=[[The Times]]|access-date=21 March 2016}}</ref> and in April 2016 she profiled the US Ambassador to the UK, [[Matthew Barzun]], also for ''[[The Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/past-six-days/2016-04-16/the-times-magazine/yes-we-can-mr-president-5gjmx7mtp|title=Yes, we can, Mr President |newspaper=[[The Times]]|access-date=19 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, she once again interviewed Prime Minister Cameron for ''The Times Magazine'', this time ahead of the European Referendum.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/five-days-to-go-whats-he-really-thinking-xsgxkznzb|title=On the campaign trail with David Cameron  |newspaper=[[The Times]]|access-date=22 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nRussell regularly appears on television and radio, on programmes such as the [[BBC]]'s ''[[Newsnight]]'' and [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s ''[[The Agenda with Tom Bradby]]'', as well as [[Sky News]].\n\n==R